[3] Nigeria - suspected cases and WHO DG statement
Date: Sun 12 Feb 2006
From: Mary Marshall <tropical.forestry@btinternet.com>
Source: Reuters Foundation AlertNet, Sun 12 Feb 2006 [edited]
<http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/L12107379.htm>

Nigeria: 2 children are H5N1 Virus Infection Suspects
-----------------------------------------------
Nigerian health officials waited anxiously on Sunday [12 Feb 2006]
for test results on 2 children feared to be the 1st Africans infected
with the deadly H5N1 bird flu virus.
The virus [appeared] in early January 2006 among poultry in Nigeria,
Africa's most populous country, but the H5N1 diagnosis was confirmed
only last week, and authorities are struggling to contain it as it
spreads rapidly to farms across the north. The father of the 2
children -- a 4-year-old boy and a baby boy of 4 months -- said they
had a very high temperature and coughed up blood 2 weeks ago when all
250 of his geese, turkey and chickens died suddenly. "The 2 of them
were coughing, and if they sneezed, blood came from their nose and
throat," Isaac Achi told Reuters. "I took them to the hospital, and
they recovered. It happened when all the birds in our surroundings
died. My wife also complained of chest pains," he said, adding that
the elder boy was now back at school. The Achi family home is close
to a farm where the H5N1 virus was confirmed.
Health Ministry official Abdulsalam Nasidi visited the children on
Sunday [12 Feb 2006] and took away a blood sample, which is due to be
analyzed at a specialist laboratory in nearby Plateau state. People
can catch the virus, which has killed at least 88 people in Asia and
the Middle East since early 2003, from contact with infected birds,
but it cannot yet be spread from one human to another.
The outbreak of H5N1 in Nigeria is the 1st known appearance of the
virus in Africa. Although only 4 farms in 3 northern Nigerian states
have confirmation of H5N1, officials believe more than 20 farms have
been hit in Kano state alone. Farmers in 3 other northern states have
also reported mass deaths of poultry, local media reported. Farmers
have received little information on how to handle the disease, and
workers have been using their bare hands to dispose of thousands of
sick birds, raising fears of a large number of human infections.
"This is an emergency situation, and it is very important to stop the
handling, trading and movement of birds," said Mohammed Belhoecine,
Nigeria representative of the World Health Organization.
[Byline: Daniel Flynn]
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Apart from these 2 suspected cases, there have been no reports of
human cases of avian influenza anywhere in Africa. - Mod.CP]
